lity. Third, I take it as axiomatic that data is best represented in ways that adhere closely to its original form, barring specific needs to the contrary. It should be evident on a practical level that this is a matter of parsimony. It is also a matter of basic linguistic philosophy; I hold that, in matters of linguistic usage, conceptual issues (“theory”) are subordinate to data and derive naturally from the handling of data, rather than the other way around. . Spoken languageNotes below refer to the spoken language. ggg I have not attempted to give a thorough description of spoken Taiwanese grammar, merely to categorize the basic relationships between sandhi juncture and syntax. All sentences and individual lexical items are numbered in italics. Sentences are first parsed grammatically, then translated literally and finally put into idiomatic English. . Stress and sandhi juncture. Final syllables in generalWith some exceptions, the last normally stressed syllable in a sentence exhibits its basic tone value..	li3		beh7		khi5	to3-ui6	[note ]	Pron	Aux		V		PW	you	want to	go		where?	“Where do you want to go?”.	in1		long3		tih7		lai6-te3	[note ]	Pron	Adv		V			Direc	they	[total]		[progr]	inside	“They’re all inside”These two sentences contain no unstressed syllables and only the final syllables have unchanaged tone values. But the issue of stress is important, because words and syllables can become tonally unstressed (pronounced in the neutral tone) in a number of situations. One case is sentence-final particles, which are regularly pronounced in the neutral tone and preceded by a syllable in its basic tone..	a	indicates completed verb aspect; .	bo/boo	indicates a simple question; .	le	indicates progressive verb aspect. [note ]Words and syllables can undergo loss of stress in a number of circumstances. The syllable immediately preceding a neutral-tone syllable usually has its basic value, but there are exceptions.. Special cases of “final